==English==

===Etymology===
From {{NL.}} ''[[logarithmus]]'', term coined by Scot mathematician [[w:John Napier|John Napier]] from {{Gr.}} [[λόγος]] (logos) "word, reason" and [[αριθμός]] (arithmos) "number".

===Noun===
# {{mathematics}} For a number <math>x</math>, the [[power]] to which a given ''[[base]]'' number must be raised in order to obtain <math>x</math>.  Written <math>\log_b x</math>.  For example, <math>\log_{10} 1000 = 3</math> because <math>10^3 = 1000</math>.

Additionally, the term "ln" is used to represent a logarith in the base e. Eg: <math> ln e = 1 </math>

